<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-completeness-axiom"
xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The Completeness Axiom</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      The following axiom is what sets the real field apart from other
      ordered fields.
    </p> 

    <axiom xml:id="ax-least-upper-bound-property">
      <title>The Completeness Axiom of <m>\R</m></title> 

      <statement>
        <p>
          Every non-empty set of real numbers that is bounded above has a
          supremum in <m>\R</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      </axiom> 

      <p>
        For an ordered set, the <term>least upper bound property</term>
        <idx><h>least upper bound property</h></idx> means:
        every non-empty subset that is bounded above has a least upper bound
        (that is, a supremum) in the set.
        So the completeness axiom says that <m>\R</m>, with its usual order,
        has the least upper bound property.
      </p>
   </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-completeness-consequences">
    <title>Consequences</title> <proposition
    xml:id="prop-completeness-infimum-equivalent">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The completeness axiom of <m>\R</m> is equivalent to: every
          non-empty subset of <m>\R</m> that is bounded below has an infimum
          in <m>\R</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>A\subseteq\R</m> be non-empty and bounded below. Then
          <m>-A</m> is non-empty and bounded above, so <m>s:=\sup(-A)</m>
          exists. We claim <m>-s=\inf A</m>.  For <m>a\in A</m>, we have
          <m>-a\in -A</m>, hence <m>-a\le s</m>, so <m>-s\le a</m>. Thus
          <m>-s</m> is a lower bound of <m>A</m>.  If <m>l</m> is any lower
          bound of <m>A</m>, then <m>-l</m> is an upper bound of <m>-A</m>,
          so <m>s\le -l</m>, i.e. <m>l\le -s</m>. Therefore <m>-s</m> is
          the greatest lower bound of <m>A</m>.
        </p> 

	<p>
          Conversely, assume every non-empty bounded-below subset of
          <m>\R</m> has an infimum. Let <m>B\subseteq\R</m> be non-empty
          and bounded above.  Then <m>-B</m> is non-empty and bounded below,
          so <m>m:=\inf(-B)</m> exists. The same argument shows <m>-m=\sup
          B</m>. Hence the least upper bound property holds.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>


    <exercise xml:id="ex-sec-completeness-sup-monotone">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>\emptyset\ne A\subseteq B\subseteq\R</m> and that
            <m>B</m> is bounded above. Show that
            <me>\inf B \le \inf A \le \sup A \le \sup B.</me>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

        <p>
          An ordered field is
          <term>Archimedean</term><idx><h>Archimedean</h></idx> if for every
          <m>x</m> in the field there exists <m>n \in \N</m> such that <m>x
          &lt; n</m>.
        </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-n-unbounded-above">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The ordered field <m>\R</m> is Archimedean.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          By the definition above, it suffices to show that for every
          <m>x \in \R</m> there exists <m>n \in \N</m> such that <m>x &lt; n</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Suppose instead that some <m>x \in \R</m> were an upper bound for
          <m>\N</m>. Then <m>\N</m> would be non-empty and bounded above, so by
          the least upper bound property, <m>u:=\sup\N</m> would exist. Since
          <m>u-1&lt;u</m>, the number <m>u-1</m> cannot be an upper bound of
          <m>\N</m>. So there is <m>n\in\N</m> with <m>u-1&lt;n</m>. Then
          <m>u&lt;n+1</m>, and <m>n+1\in\N</m>, contradicting that <m>u</m> is
          an upper bound of <m>\N</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Therefore <m>\N</m> is not bounded above in <m>\R</m>, and hence
          <m>\R</m> is Archimedean.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-archimedean-property">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For any <m>x \in \R</m> and any <m>\varepsilon &gt; 0</m>, there
          exists <m>N \in \N</m> such that <m>N\varepsilon &gt; x</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Since <m>\varepsilon &gt; 0</m>, the number <m>x/\varepsilon</m> is
          real. By <xref ref="prop-n-unbounded-above"/>, there exists
          <m>N \in \N</m> such that <m>N &gt; x/\varepsilon</m>. Multiplying by
          <m>\varepsilon</m> gives <m>N\varepsilon &gt; x</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-reciprocal-archimedean">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For any <m>\varepsilon &gt; 0</m>, there exists <m>n \in \N</m> such
          that <m>1/n &lt; \varepsilon</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Apply <xref ref="prop-archimedean-property"/> with <m>x=1</m>. Then
          there exists <m>n \in \N</m> such that <m>n\varepsilon &gt; 1</m>.
          Since <m>n&gt;0</m>, dividing by <m>n\varepsilon</m> yields
          <m>1/n &lt; \varepsilon</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-integer-part">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For any <m>x \in \R</m>, there exists <m>n \in \Z</m> such that
          <m>n \le x &lt; n+1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          By <xref ref="prop-n-unbounded-above"/>, there exists <m>N \in \N</m>
          such that <m>N &gt; |x|</m>. Then <m>-N &lt; x &lt; N</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Consider the finite set
          <me>S=\{-N,-N+1,\dots,0,\dots,N\}\subseteq\Z.</me>
          Since <m>-N \le x</m>, the set of integers in <m>S</m> that are at
          most <m>x</m> is non-empty. Let <m>n</m> be the largest such integer.
        </p>
        <p>
          Then <m>n \le x</m>. Also <m>n \ne N</m>, because <m>x &lt; N</m>.
          Hence <m>n+1 \in S</m>. By maximality of <m>n</m>, the integer
          <m>n+1</m> cannot satisfy <m>n+1 \le x</m>. Therefore
          <m>x &lt; n+1</m>, and so <m>n \le x &lt; n+1</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-integer-between-reals">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For any <m>x,y \in \R</m>, if <m>y-x &gt; 1</m>, then there exists
          <m>m \in \Z</m> such that <m>x \le m &lt; y</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          By <xref ref="prop-integer-part"/>, there exists <m>n \in \Z</m>
          such that <m>n \le x &lt; n+1</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          If <m>y \le n+1</m>, then
          <me>n \le x &lt; y \le n+1,</me>
          so <m>y-x &lt; (n+1)-n = 1</m>, contradicting the hypothesis.
          Therefore <m>n+1 &lt; y</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Let <m>m=n+1</m>. Then <m>m \in \Z</m> and
          <m>x &lt; m &lt; y</m>. In particular, <m>x \le m &lt; y</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <p>
	A subset <m>D</m> of <m>\R</m> is <term>dense</term> <idx> <h>dense</h>
	</idx> if between any two real numbers lies an element of <m>D</m>.
    </p> 

    <proposition xml:id="prop-q-dense-in-r">
      <statement>
	<p>
	  The set <m>\Q</m> is dense in <m>\R</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>x,y \in \R</m> with <m>x&lt;y</m>. Then <m>y-x&gt;0</m>, so by
          <xref ref="prop-archimedean-property"/> there exists <m>N \in \N</m>
          such that <m>N(y-x)&gt;1</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Applying <xref ref="prop-integer-between-reals"/> to the numbers
          <m>Nx</m> and <m>Ny</m>, we obtain an integer <m>m</m> such that
          <m>Nx &lt; m &lt; Ny</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Since <m>N&gt;0</m>, dividing by <m>N</m> gives
          <m>x &lt; m/N &lt; y</m>. Because <m>m/N \in \Q</m>, this proves that
          <m>\Q</m> is dense in <m>\R</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-positive-square-root-existence">
      <title>Existence of Positive Square Roots</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For each <m>a&gt;0</m>, there exists a unique <m>u&gt;0</m> such that
          <m>u^2=a</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Uniqueness is immediate because <m>x\mapsto x^2</m> is strictly
          increasing on <m>(0,\infty)</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          For existence, define
          <m>S=\{x\in\R : x&gt;0,\ x^2\le a\}</m>. The set is non-empty:
          if <m>a\ge 1</m>, then <m>1\in S</m>; if <m>0&lt;a&lt;1</m>, then
          <m>a\in S</m>. It is bounded above by <m>M=\max\{a,1\}</m>, since
          <m>x&gt;M</m> implies <m>x^2&gt;a</m>. By completeness, <m>u:=\sup S</m>
          exists.
        </p>

        <p>
          If <m>u^2&lt;a</m>, then for sufficiently small <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m>,
          we still have <m>(u+\varepsilon)^2\le a</m>, so <m>u+\varepsilon\in S</m>,
          contradicting that <m>u</m> is an upper bound of <m>S</m>. If
          <m>u^2&gt;a</m>, then for sufficiently small <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m>,
          <m>(u-\varepsilon)^2&gt;a</m>; then every <m>x\in S</m> satisfies
          <m>x\le u-\varepsilon</m>, so <m>u-\varepsilon</m> is an upper bound
          of <m>S</m>, contradicting leastness of <m>u</m>. Hence
          <m>u^2=a</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      A standard comparison example is the ordered field
      <m>\Q</m>:
      the set <m>\{q\in\Q:q&gt;0,\ q^2&lt;2\}</m> is non-empty and bounded above
      in <m>\Q</m>, but it has no supremum in <m>\Q</m>.
      Therefore <m>\Q</m> does not satisfy the least upper bound property.
    </p>
  </subsection>

</section>
